<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-007-188 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 613 742</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 25 1991 v25 n47 p74(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Research tax credit in danger; deadline nears.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two committees in the US Congress want to extend the research andexperimental (Randamp;E) tax credit, among other incentives, for oneyear.andP;  The committees have introduced legislation, but manycomputer industry firms are worried that if the bills do not pass,they will face significantly higher tax bills in 1992.andP;  Appleestimates that it spends approximately $500 million each year onRandamp;E.andP;  Research would continue, but projects involving riskyinvestments will probably be sacrificed among firms in theindustry.andP;  The challenge facing Randamp;E tax incentive supporters inthe Congress is where to locate other offsetting tax revenue.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Tax DeductionResearch and DevelopmentUnited States. Congress. Senate.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>